"""Batch planner task definition (Mike's `batchPlanner`, task 188168584594), embedded for LOCAL in-process execution in studio_server.

This is the local stand-in for the kiln_server-hosted copilot task. When the
batch plan call is moved to GCP/kiln_server, this module is no longer used —
kiln_server serves the bundled copy under
`static/kiln_projects/copilot/tasks/188168584594 - BatchPlanner/` instead.
Keep the two in sync until the GCP switch.
"""

BATCH_PLAN_INSTRUCTION = 'You are creating a batch plan for generating synthetic inputs for a task.\n\nYou will receive:\n- The input data guide in <input_data_guide> tags\n- The task\'s input schema in <task_input_schema> tags (may be absent)\n- The task\'s output schema in <task_output_schema> tags (may be absent — describes\n  what the task PRODUCES from each input; context only, never generate outputs)\n- The task\'s instructions in <task_instruction> tags (this tells\n  you what the inputs are USED FOR; do NOT generate the task\'s output)\n- User guidance for this specific batch in <user_guidance> tags\n- Number of inputs to generate in <count> tags (N)\n\nA synthetic input is one example of the data that will be fed into the task at\nruntime. You turn high-level guidance into a set of N (<count>) specific prompts — one per\ninput — that a downstream generator each expands into a single realistic\nsynthetic input.\n\nHOW EACH PROMPT IS USED (read carefully):\nEach prompt you write is slotted in after a fixed instruction, roughly:\n  "Generate a synthetic input matching: <your prompt>"\nThe generator ALSO receives the full input data guide (and schema). Therefore:\n- Write each prompt as a DESCRIPTION of what makes THAT input distinct — not as a\n  standalone command. Do NOT begin with "Generate...", "Create...", "Write...",\n  or any imperative.\n- Include ONLY what VARIES across inputs. Do NOT restate attributes that are true\n  of EVERY input — the input type, universal formatting/wrapping, or any\n  constant the data guide already fixes for all inputs. The generator gets those\n  from the data guide; repeating them in every prompt is noise.\n- If a detail would be identical in all N prompts, it does not belong in any of\n  them.\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nFIRST: IDENTIFY INPUT TYPE\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nBefore anything else, determine if <user_guidance> specifies a DIFFERENT input type:\n1. INPUT TYPE REQUESTS in guidance:\n   - Explicit: "make them support tickets", "generate call transcripts instead of\n     emails", "write these as forum posts", etc.\n   - Naming a specific genre/format for the input indicates an input type change\n   - The input data guide\'s type is DEFAULT, a user-specified type OVERRIDES\n   - NOTE: a tone or style tweak ("make them more casual") is NOT a type change —\n     that\'s content/format guidance, handled lower in the cascade\n2. INPUT DATA GUIDE TYPE PRESERVATION:\n   - If no input type mentioned → use the data guide\'s type (default behavior)\n   - If an input type is specified → use that type entirely, the data guide\n     provides style/domain only\n3. SCHEMA PINS STRUCTURE:\n   - If <task_input_schema> is present, the input STRUCTURE is fixed by the schema\n     and CANNOT be overridden. An input-type override applies only to free-form\n     (schema-less) inputs. With a schema, user guidance still steers content,\n     style, and distribution — but never the shape.\nWrite your determination:\n"INPUT TYPE: [data guide type or user-specified type]"\n"SOURCE: [data guide semantics + user style] or [user semantics + data guide style]"\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nAUTHORITY CASCADE (use this to resolve ALL conflicts)\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nWhen instructions conflict, the HIGHER source wins — no exceptions:\n1. task_input_schema (when present) → defines the REQUIRED STRUCTURE: field names,\n   types, required vs optional, enums, formats. Never overridden.\n2. Input type from user → OVERRIDES the data guide\'s default type\n   (free-form inputs only; user says "call transcripts" → generate transcripts)\n3. User guidance for content/format → OVERRIDES data guide defaults\n   (For BOTH static template AND dynamic variable content)\n4. Input data guide → BASELINE when user doesn\'t specify\nINVARIANTS (never overridden):\n- Conformance to task_input_schema (fields, types, required, enums, formats)\n- Logical relationships between fields\n- Critical constraints and dependencies\n- Domain plausibility and accuracy\n"Maintain data guide patterns" = use the data guide WHERE USER HASN\'T SPECIFIED.\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nHOW THE DATA GUIDE AND SCHEMA RELATE\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nWhen <task_input_schema> is present, it is the authoritative source for field\nnames, top-level types, required vs optional, cardinality, enums, and any value\nformats it states explicitly. The input data guide deliberately does NOT restate\nanything the schema already captures. Treat them as complementary:\n- Schema = the exact structure and field-level constraints every input must satisfy.\n- Data guide = everything the schema can\'t express — realistic content,\n  distributions, relationships, plausibility.\nTogether they define a valid input. Only plan inputs the schema can represent.\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nUSING THE TASK OUTPUT SCHEMA (context only)\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nWhen <task_output_schema> is present, its fields and especially their DESCRIPTIONS\noften carry domain context the task instruction omits — what the task\ndiscriminates, the categories/ranges it produces, and the edge cases that matter.\nUse it for two things:\n- REALISM: plan inputs that could plausibly produce a valid output under this schema.\n- COVERAGE: spread the batch so it exercises the meaningful range of outputs — e.g.\n  inputs that would land on different enum values, boundary cases, and the\n  situations the output descriptions call out — instead of clustering on one.\nHard limits:\n- NEVER generate the task\'s output, label, or answer. You plan INPUTS only.\n- Do NOT engineer inputs to be artificially easy or to telegraph a specific output.\n  Realistic inputs — including ambiguous or hard ones — are the goal, not\n  label-leaking ones.\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nINTERPRET THE GUIDANCE: GENERATIVE vs. FAILURE-MODE\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n<user_guidance> comes in two flavors — detect which, because they demand different batch compositions:\n\n1. GENERATIVE / DISTRIBUTION request — asks for a kind of data or an explicit spread\n   (e.g. "make 10 medical records across a wide range of genders"). Plan the batch to\n   COVER that variety directly, in the requested proportions.\n\n2. FAILURE-MODE / SPEC-COVERAGE request — the guidance (often WITH a spec: its rules,\n   constraints, and pass/fail examples) asks you to test whether the model gets a behavior\n   right, or names a bug it makes. The batch is a TEST SET, so give it discriminating power\n   along the SPEC\'S OWN pass/fail boundary:\n   - FIRST derive that boundary from the spec: which input property makes the task SUCCEED\n     vs FAIL (including any stated constraint and the situations the pass/fail examples\n     illustrate). The two "sides" are inputs that DO vs DO NOT trigger that behavior/failure.\n     Example: if a spec says "inputs that mix several unrelated topics must get a single\n     unified summary", the sides are multi-topic inputs (failure-prone) vs single-topic\n     inputs (easy) — the axis is topic-mixing (what the spec turns on), nothing else.\n   - A "balanced split (≈50/50)" means ≈half on EACH SIDE OF THAT SPEC BOUNDARY. It does\n     NOT mean literal positive/negative sentiment, mood, or tone, and NOT any attribute the\n     spec does not care about. Do NOT spend the batch varying an axis that doesn\'t change\n     the pass/fail outcome — that is wasted coverage. The axis that matters is the one the\n     spec\'s rules and examples turn on.\n   - Do NOT put 100% of inputs on one side: without both sides you cannot tell a real\n     failure from a model that always answers the same way. ≈50/50 is the default; you may\n     lean toward the failure-prone side to cover its distinct sub-conditions, but keep the\n     control side at roughly a third or more. Spread each side realistically; don\'t make the\n     easy side trivial.\n   - Cover EACH distinct pass/fail condition and stated CONSTRAINT the spec names with at\n     least one input (e.g. a character/length limit, a required element). For a constraint\n     on the OUTPUT, plan an input whose ideal output would PUSH AGAINST it (e.g. to test a\n     short length limit, an input whose natural correct answer is long). A condition the\n     spec calls out but the batch never exercises is a coverage hole — before returning,\n     check every named condition and constraint has ≥1 input and repurpose any redundant\n     slot to close a gap.\n   - The batch must CONTAIN both sides (for discriminating power), but the SUMMARY does NOT\n     lead with that pass/fail split — it describes the substantive coverage (see SUMMARY).\n     The pass/fail balance is internal eval hygiene, not what the user asked about.\n\nIf the guidance is ambiguous between the two, prefer balanced coverage — it is safe for both.\n═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nYour task:\n1. Create a "summary" field: a short, polished overview of the batch for the user\n2. Create a "prompts" array with SPECIFIC, CONCRETE guidance for EACH individual input\nCRITICAL: Each prompt must be a SPECIFIC INSTANTIATION of user guidance, not a repetition.\nSUMMARY: A short, polished, user-facing overview of the batch, shown directly in\nthe UI — a clean, finished summary, not internal notes or scratch work. Keep it tight:\none lead line + a handful of label:share bullets, ~5–8 short lines total.\n- Lead line: ONE short sentence that SUMMARIZES THE MIX — NOT a restatement of the\n  count/purpose ("Generating N…", "…across N signals") and NOT a trailing list of\n  dimensions. If an eval, spec, or target is named, put ITS NAME in **bold**. One line.\n- Then a tight bulleted breakdown of the composition. Each bullet is a **bold category\n  label** + its share (percentage and/or count). PREFER to stop there — the members are\n  already listed in the prompts array. NEVER write a descriptive clause per member\n  (restating what each input is); at most add a few comma-separated KEYWORDS if they add\n  real information the label doesn\'t.\n    BAD  (verbose clause per member): "**Type A:** 37% (3) — a tightly-unified case with low\n      variation, a case spanning one family\'s sub-styles, a cohesive case with a twist"\n    GOOD (nothing, or terse keywords): "**Type A:** 37% (3)"  or  "**Type A:** 37% (3) — X, Y, Z"\n  One short line per bullet; keep the whole summary to ~5–8 short lines.\n- The bullets must PARTITION the batch: mutually-exclusive categories whose shares sum to\n  ~100%, not overlapping buckets that overflow the total. If an edge case cross-cuts a main\n  category, list it separately as "plus N …", never as an overlapping percentage.\n- Use percentages/counts (e.g. "50% type X, 30% type Y") so the mix is graspable\n  at a glance.\n- Break the batch down along the DIMENSIONS THE SPEC/GUIDANCE CARES ABOUT — the meaningful\n  coverage axes (the conditions, categories, regions, edge cases, and behaviors the spec\n  highlights). That is what the user wants to see. Do NOT reduce the breakdown to a pass/fail\n  (positive-vs-negative, reject-vs-publish) split — that balance is internal eval hygiene the\n  user is not tracking; at most mention it as a brief secondary aside, never as the breakdown.\n- NO internal jargon ("data guide", "corpus", "off book", "schema", "authority\n  cascade") and NO meta-commentary about your process.\nExample summary (illustrates FORMAT only — invent your own content):\n  Skews toward high-value edge cases across three vendor types.\n  - **Beer/wine suppliers:** 50% (25)\n  - **Caterers:** 25% (13)\n  - **Woodworking shops:** 25% (12)\n  - **Extended termination clauses:** ~15%\nWhen instantiating guidance:\n1. ALWAYS respect CRITICAL SEMANTIC CONSTRAINTS from the data guide and schema:\n   - Schema conformance must be maintained (fields, types, required, enums, formats)\n   - Field dependencies must be maintained\n   - Logical consistency must be preserved\n   - Context-appropriate values must be used\n2. Handle generation mode based on user guidance:\n   - FAITHFUL generation: Pick values matching typical data guide patterns\n   - DIVERGENT generation: When user requests edge cases or unusual combinations, respect divergence while maintaining logical consistency\n3. PRESENTATION/FORMAT HANDLING:\n   User guidance can specify format EXPLICITLY or IMPLICITLY:\n   EXPLICIT: Direct statements about format, structure, or regional conventions\n   IMPLICIT: Values/units/formats used in guidance ARE format signal.\n   When user guidance uses specific units, date formats, terminology, or\n   conventions, those choices define the output format. Do NOT convert them\n   back to data guide defaults.\n   CRITICAL RULES:\n   A. PRESERVE format signals: If user guidance uses specific formats, units, or\n      conventions, your prompts MUST continue using those. Do NOT convert back to\n      data guide defaults.\n   B. COMPLETE STANDARD: A regional/style request means ALL conventions from that\n      standard, not just explicitly mentioned fields.\n   C. STRUCTURAL FORMATS ARE VALID: Requests about section ordering, omissions,\n      or input organization are presentation requirements. Include them in\n      prompt guidance.\n4. INPUT TYPE SPECIFIC GUIDANCE:\nWhen user requests a DIFFERENT input type (free-form inputs only; e.g., "make\nthese call transcripts"):\n- Structure prompts to reflect the REQUESTED input type\'s structure\n- The data guide contributes: writing style, domain knowledge, quality standards\n- Example: If the data guide describes support emails and guidance says "call\n  transcripts", prompts should describe spoken back-and-forth, not email content\n- BAD prompt: "Subject line, greeting, body paragraph about a billing dispute..."\n  (this keeps the data guide\'s email structure)\n- GOOD prompt: "Transcript of a 4-minute call: customer disputes a $42 billing\n  charge, agent looks up the account, identifies a duplicate charge, issues a\n  refund, customer thanks them..."\n  (this uses transcript structure with the data guide\'s domain knowledge)\nEach prompt should:\n- State ONLY the distinguishing variables for this input — the concrete values and\n  attributes that VARY. Do NOT include any rationale, justification, "because…",\n  explanation of what the input tests, or the expected output/label/answer — that is\n  reasoning, and stating the expected outcome leaks the answer. Never name "the spec",\n  "the failure scenario/pattern", "edge case", "control", or "trigger", and never add a\n  parenthetical explaining what the input is for. The prompt describes the input, never\n  why it is in the batch. Also ban phrasings that state the input\'s PURPOSE, the\n  condition it covers, or its expected difficulty — e.g. "tests the …",\n  "stresses/pushes against the … limit", "…-failure risk", "prime case for …",\n  "requires a high-level summary" — and never include an example of the expected\n  output. Which condition a group targets belongs in the SUMMARY, never in a prompt.\n  Convert any such intent into a neutral INPUT PROPERTY (e.g. not "tests the 50-char\n  limit" but "a change whose natural one-line summary is long and verbose").\n- Describe the input by its VARIABLES OF INTEREST — its position on the axes that vary\n  (type, size, cohesion, difficulty, which spec condition it exercises) — NOT the finished\n  input. Do NOT pre-write the input\'s surface content: do NOT enumerate the actual items,\n  records, captions, rows, or sentences. Materializing that content is the downstream\n  generator\'s job; hand it the shape and characteristics, not the contents. For a\n  collection input, give count + cohesion + difficulty, not each element.\n- Treat any examples in the spec/guidance as ILLUSTRATIONS of the behavior, not content to\n  reuse: generate novel, independent inputs; never reproduce or lightly reskin a provided\n  example (it wastes coverage and telegraphs the expected output).\n- Be distinct from other prompts (no copy-paste repetition)\n- Include ONLY the per-input variation — never restate constants shared by all\n  inputs (input type, universal formatting/wrapping, anything the data guide\n  fixes for every input). Those come from the data guide the generator also sees.\n- Be phrased as a description of the distinct input, NOT an imperative command\n  (no leading "Generate...", "Create...", "Write...")\n- Give specific values for the VARIABLES that vary (e.g. "6 items", "single\n  tightly-related theme", "high difficulty"), not vague ranges — but this is NOT license\n  to write the input\'s full content; specify the variables and let the generator produce it\n- When a prompt diverges from the usual inputs in any MEASURABLE way (length,\n  verbosity, section counts, value ranges), state EXPLICIT numeric bounds, not\n  vague qualifiers. BAD: "much longer and more detailed." GOOD: "expand to\n  100-150 words, 5-7 sentences (usual: ~40 words)."\n- Conform to task_input_schema when present (valid fields, types, enums, formats)\n- Add realistic secondary details from the data guide\n- Tell a slightly different story while satisfying user guidance\n- RESPECT all critical semantic constraints\n- PRESERVE all format/presentation requirements from user guidance\n- VARY AUXILIARY/CONDITIONAL DATA: Spread variable elements across the batch —\n  don\'t default to the most common pattern for every prompt. Draw these axes from\n  BOTH sources: the schema (optional fields — include in some, omit in others; and\n  enums — spread the allowed values across the batch), and the data guide (any\n  sections or data subtypes it marks as conditional or variable). Diversify what\n  types of auxiliary data appear, not just the primary content.\nBAD prompts (imperative framing, restating a constant true of every input, and\njust echoing the guidance — note "<shared input type/format>" is fixed by the data\nguide for ALL inputs, so it\'s noise, and the two prompts are interchangeable):\n- Prompt 1: "Generate one <shared input type/format> with characteristic A in range X-Y"\n- Prompt 2: "Generate one <shared input type/format> with characteristic A in range X-Y"\nGOOD prompts (no command, no shared constants — only the concrete per-input\nvariation, with format signals preserved and conditional data varied):\n- Prompt 1: "Entity P: A = X (in the requested units), constraint Y satisfied, plus\n  distinguishing context C"\n- Prompt 2: "Entity Q: A = X\' (a different value), optional section D included this\n  time, constraint Y still satisfied, different context E"\nDo NOT pre-write the input\'s content — that is the generator\'s job. For a COLLECTION\ninput (a set/list of elements), name the collection\'s SHAPE, never its individual\nelements — not even a few "for example" items:\n- BAD (names the elements — content the generator should invent): "8 tracks: a jazz\n  standard, a rock anthem, a lullaby, a techno beat, a folk ballad, an opera aria, a rap\n  verse, an ambient loop"\n- GOOD (shape only — count, cohesion, spread, difficulty): "8 tracks, single\n  tightly-unified genre, low difficulty" or "8 tracks spanning 8 unrelated genres — no\n  shared mood, era, or style"\nNaming even a handful of representative elements is STILL content — give the category and\nspread instead. Do NOT invent or foreground a FREE-FORM attribute the spec does not score\n(e.g. tacking a "positive/negative mood" onto every input for a task about puns) — that is\nnoise. This is DIFFERENT from a real schema field the input actually has (e.g. a `sentiment`\nor `date` field): populate and vary those for realism, just never let an off-spec attribute\nbecome the batch\'s organizing axis.\n\nReturn ONLY a JSON object:\n{\n  "prompts": ["guidance for input 1", "guidance for input 2", ..., "guidance for input N"]\n  "summary": "Short, polished, user-facing overview of the batch...",\n}'

BATCH_PLAN_OUTPUT_SCHEMA = '{"type":"object","properties":{"prompts":{"type":"array","description":"One entry per input to generate; the array length must equal the requested count. Each entry drives the generation of a single synthetic input.","items":{"type":"string","description":"A single generation prompt describing ONLY what makes this one input distinct from the others (the per-input variation). Written as a description of the input, not an imperative command - no leading \'Generate\', \'Create\', or \'Write\'. Must not restate attributes shared by every input (the input type, universal formatting/wrapping, or anything the data guide fixes for all inputs), since the downstream generator also receives the data guide. Uses specific concrete values rather than ranges or placeholders, conforms to the task input schema when one is present, preserves any format signals from the user guidance, and states explicit numeric bounds for any measurable divergence from the usual inputs. States ONLY the distinguishing variables — no rationale, justification, or expected output/label. Describes the input\'s distinguishing variables (its axis positions: type, size, cohesion, difficulty), not the input\'s full surface content - do not enumerate the actual items, records, or captions."}},"summary":{"type":"string","description":"A short, polished, user-facing overview of the batch, shown directly in the UI. Lead with ONE sentence summarizing the composition (not a restatement of count/purpose like \'generating N to test the spec\'); bold the eval/spec/target name if one is named. Follow with a tight bulleted breakdown: each bullet is a bold category label then ONLY its share (percentage and/or count) and NOTHING after the count - no explanation, and no list of the bucket\'s individual members (those are in the prompts array). For a failure-mode/eval batch, state the positive/negative split explicitly. Must read concise and finished, not scratch work. Do not use internal jargon (e.g. \'data guide\', \'corpus\', \'schema\', \'off book\', \'authority cascade\') and do not include meta-commentary about the planning process."}},"required":["prompts","summary"],"additionalProperties":false}'
